-> pidstat:
-----------

-> Introduction:

    -> The pidstat command in Linux is used to monitor the performance of individual processes and tasks. It provides detailed statistics about:

        => CPU usage
        => Memory usage
        => Disk I/O activity
        => Process scheduling
        => Thread activity

-> The command pidstat is very useful for:

        => Troubleshooting system performance
        => Identifying resource-heavy processes
        => Monitoring process behavior in real time
        => Performance analysis in servers

->  Syntax:

        # pidstat [option] [interval] [count]
    
    -> Installing pidstat command:

        # apt install sysstat (Ubuntu/ Debian)

        # yum/dnf install sysstat (RHEL, CentOS)

-> Monitor every 2 seconds:

    # pidstat 2

-> Monitor a specific PID:

    # pidstat -p <PID>

-> Monitor multiple PIDs:

    # pidstat -p <PID1>,<PID2>

-> Monitor all PIDs:

    # pidstat -p ALL

-> Use Cases:

    System Administration:

        => Detect high CPU processes
        => Monitor memory leaks
        => Analyze disk-intensive applications

    Cybersecurity:

        => Detect suspicious processes
        => Identify hidden resource-consuming malware
        => Monitor abnormal system activity

    Performance Tuning

        => Optimize server applications
        => Analyze workload distribution
